        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-container">
            <h3>Should I calculate the tip before or after tax?</h3>
            <p>According to standard hospitality etiquette, you should calculate your tip strictly based on the pre-tax subtotal. You are tipping the server for the food and service provided, not tipping them on the localized government sales tax.</p>
            
            <h3>What is the standard tipping rate currently?</h3>
            <p>In the United States, 15% is the recognized baseline for standard service, while 18% to 20% is expected for good to excellent service. Tips for takeout or counter service typically range from 10% to 15%.</p>
            
            <h3>Does rounding up change the percentage heavily?</h3>
            <p>Rounding your payment to a clean whole dollar amount is common, but on very small bills it can drastically alter the actual percentage. Rounding a $4.50 coffee up to $6.00 is technically a 33% tip!</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>Knowing how to calculate tip amounts seamlessly removes the stress from dining out and guarantees your service workers are compensated ethically. By mastering the 10% mental decimal shift, applying standard addition rules, and utilizing digital split-calculators for massive group tabs, you ensure every financial interaction at checkout is perfectly accurate.</p>
